The '''Tajihi clan''' (多治比氏 ''Tajihi-uji''; also written as 多治, 丹比, 丹治, 丹墀) was a Japanese noble family.
== Name == The name of the Tajihi clan can be written with various combinations of [[kanji]], including 多治比, 多治, 丹比, 丹治, and 丹墀.{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} The clan were descendants of [[Prince Tajihiko]],{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} who, according to tradition, was named for the ''tajihi'' (多治比, [[Fallopia japonica|Japanese knotweed]]) blossoms that were blown by at the time of his birth,{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} but it seems more likely that the clan were name for Tajihi District (丹比郡) in [[Kawachi Province]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}}
== History == The Tajihi clan's ancestor Prince Tajihiko was a great-grandson of the sixth-century [[Emperor Senka]] through his son [[Prince Kamueha]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} The clan's original ''[[kabane]]'' was ''Kimi'' (公),{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} but were given the title ''[[Mahito]]'' (or ''Mabito'') by [[Emperor Tenmu]] in 684.{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}}
{{illm|Tajihi no Shima|ja|多治比嶋}}, who served at the courts of Emperor Tenmu, [[Empress Jitō]] and [[Emperor Monmu]], rose to the prestigious rank of [[sadaijin|Minister of the Left]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} His sons Ikemori (多治比池守), Agatamori (多治比県守), Hironari (多治比広成), Hirotari (多治比広足) held various key positions at court, including ''[[dainagon]]'' and ''[[chūnagon]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}}
Until the middle of the [[Nara period]] the Tajihi were one of the clans at the pinnacle of court society, but after this time became increasingly overshadowed by the [[Fujiwara clan]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} Around the start of the [[Heian period]] the Tajihi clan mostly disappeared from the court society.{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} The {{illm|Tantō|ja|丹党}}, a group of warriors in [[Musashi Province]] and one of the so-called {{illm|Musashi Shichitō|ja|武蔵七党}}, were remote descendants of the Tajihi clan who took up martial ways.{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}}
