{{illm|Tajihi no Shima|ja|多治比嶋}}, who served at the courts of Emperor Tenmu, [[:en:Empress Jitō|Empress Jitō]] and [[:en:Emperor Monmu|Emperor Monmu]], rose to the prestigious Rank of [[sadaijin|Minister of the Left]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} His sons Ikemori (多治比池守), Agatamori (多治比県守), Hironari (多治比広成), Hirotari (多治比広足) held various key positions at court, including ''[[:en:Dainagon|Dainagon]]'' and ''[[:en:Chūnagon|Chūnagon]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} [[Tajihi no Mamune]] (多治比真宗, 769–823), a great-granddaughter of Ikemori, served as a consort of [[Emperor Kanmu]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}}
Until the middle of the [[Nara period]] the Tajihi were one of the clans at the pinnacle of court society, but after this time became increasingly overshadowed by the [[Fujiwara clan]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} Around the start of the [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]] the Tajihi clan mostly disappeared from the court society.{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}} The {{illm|Tantō clan|ja|丹党}}, a group of warriors in [[Musashi Province]] and one of the so-called {{illm|Musashi Shichitō|ja|武蔵七党}}, were remote descendants of the Tajihi clan who took up martial ways.{{sfnm|1a1=Mayuzumi|1y=1994}}
